If the mistress of a house did not look up her stores, it was not because she had not the keys of the apartments3 for the keys of them all, with the exception of those of the wine- ceum, were given to a Roman woman when she first entered her husband’s house aster marriage. Hence, when a wife was divorced, the keys were taken from her (Cicero Philipp. 2, 28)2 and when she separated from her husband she sent them back. Indeed keys were used in very early times, and were probably in- troduced into Greece from Egypt. Pliny, however, records the name of Theo- dorus of Samos as the inventor, the person to whom the art of fusing bronze is ascribed by Pausanias.
